  "prompt": "Is every fossil a missing link?",
  "response": "Not every fossil is considered a \"missing link.\" The term \"missing link\" is often used in popular science to describe transitional fossils that exhibit traits common to both an ancestral group and its derived descendant group. These fossils help scientists understand evolutionary relationships and the transitions between major groups of organisms.\n\nHowever, the fossil record is incomplete, and not every fossil represents a direct ancestor or a specific transitional form. Many fossils simply represent extinct species that may or may not be directly related to the lineages of living organisms. Each fossil provides valuable information about the diversity of life in the past and the evolutionary history of specific lineages, but only certain fossils can be classified as \"missing links\" in the context of illustrating evolutionary transitions.",
